============================================================

Written to `tools/title-loop/docs/10-d73df28/feedback.md`. Here's the summary:

## Failure 1: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM → "CHLEBEK"

**Root cause: 25-candidate pre-filter cuts the actual title.** The document has 6+ short all-caps section headers ("WARZYWA I BOCZEK", "DLA 4 OSÓB", "GOTOWANIE 30 MIN", "OCZEKIWANIE 1 GODZ. 30 MIN", etc.) that all pass hard filters because `looksLikeMetadata` is English-only. With 36 lines generating 30+ candidates, the pre-filter kicks in and sorts all-caps by word count (≤5 words first). The actual title has **6 words** — it's ranked last among all-caps and gets cut. With it absent from the pool, `firstStructuralHeading` resolves to something else, the prefix filter never fires to remove the standalone "CHLEBEK" section header, and "CHLEBEK" wins.

## Failure 2: Faszerowana papryka → "NA 3 PAPRYKI"

**Root cause: "NA 3 PAPRYKI" (Polish for "FOR 3 PEPPERS") is unrecognized serving-size metadata.** `looksLikeMetadata` only has English patterns (SERVES, MAKES, YIELDS). "NA 3 PAPRYKI" passes all hard filters, receives the all-caps bonus (+0.08), and in the multi-title guard's "single all-caps → pick highest score" branch, it beats the mixed-case correct title which has no bonus.

## Common themes across both failures

1. **Polish-only metadata not filtered** — `looksLikeMetadata` covers no Polish patterns
2. **Pre-filter's "short first" sort penalizes multi-word titles** — operates before quality scoring, can't distinguish headers from real titles
3. **All-caps bonus amplifies headers** — applies equally to section headers, serving sizes, and actual titles
4. **Prefix filter has a voided-upstream precondition** — only works if the full title survived the pre-filter, which it didn't in Failure 1
