nia główne\" itself passes the garbled text filter. It's mixed case, and while \"główne\" starts with a lowercase letter, the garbled word detection looks for words with enough consonants after stripping non-letters—and \"główne\" only has 4 consonants, which doesn't meet the threshold for being flagged as garbled.\n\nWhen combined with \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" into a single line, the result would still pass the hard filters and become a candidate, but the deduplication logic would eliminate it in favor of the shorter single-line version.\n\nLet me stop speculating and focus on what the code actually shows. Looking at Failure 2, I see \"Faszerowana papryka\" should be selected but instead \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" is returned. The input has the Polish title at position 0 followed by \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" at position 1, which is exactly the bilingual pattern the detection logic is meant to handle.\n\nTracing through the logic: the function correctly identifies \"Faszerowana papryka\" as a non-capitalized entry at position 0, and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" as all-caps at position 1, so the bilingual detection should trigger and select the Polish title. The filter removes \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" and similar candidates from the scoring pool, allowing \"Faszerowana papryka\" to compete on its own merits without the inflated threshold that the bilingual match would have created.\n\nNow I'm checking whether \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" - a serving size notation at position 5 - passes the hard filters. It's 10 characters long and all uppercase letters, so it clears the length and capitalization checks, but I need to verify it doesn't match any of the metadata or measurement patterns that would disqualify it.\n\nLooking at the metadata patterns, they're all English-focused (SERVES, MAKES, YIELDS), so they don't catch \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" which is Polish for \"FOR 3 PEPPERS\" - a serving size indicator that should be filtered out. That's the core issue: the filter is missing Polish serving size patterns like the \"NA [number]\" format. For the garbled text check, extracting just the letters gives \"NAPAPRYKI\" with 4 vowels out of 9 characters, which I need to evaluate against the garbling threshold.\n\nNow I'm checking whether \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" qualifies as a structural heading - it's all caps with three words, so I need to count how many are significant uppercase words to see if it meets the structural heading criteria. So \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" isn't a structural heading since \"NA\" only has 2 uppercase letters, falling short of the 4-letter requirement. It does get the all-caps bonus of 0.08, but that's not enough to make it a structural heading. Now I'm trying to understand why this serving size notation would score higher than \"Faszerowana papryka,\" which is the actual recipe title and has a strong position factor.\n\nThe key is that the filtering uses `scoredForThreshold` rather than the full `scored` object, so \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" gets excluded from the threshold calculation entirely. \"Faszerowana papryka\" remains in `scoredForThreshold` since it wasn't suppressed by bilingual detection. If \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" ends up with a higher score than \"Faszerowana papryka\" and both pass the threshold, then in the multi-title guard, only \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" would be in the all-caps selected list.\n\nWhen `allCapsSelected.length === 1`, the code picks the highest-scoring candidate overall, which would be \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" if it scored higher. The real problem is that \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" is a Polish serving size indicator that the metadata detection doesn't catch—the patterns only cover English, so a line starting with \"NA\" (Polish for \"FOR\") followed by a number slips through undetected.\n\nI'm also wondering if the bilingual detection is actually working correctly here. The logic should only suppress all-caps translation candidates, not the mixed-case \"Faszerowana papryka\" at position 0. Let me trace through what position 0 actually refers to in the line