ly determinable. The full phrase \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" either fails the threshold check outright, or it gets filtered out somewhere in the selection process, leaving just \"CHLEBEK\" as the top all-caps result. I should also check whether it might be failing the hard filters — the length constraint is worth examining here. The vowel ratio of 0.32 passes the garbled check. Now I'm verifying the multi-word validation—checking if any words start with lowercase letters or if there are sentence fragments. All words in \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" start uppercase, so it's not flagged as garbled.\n\nI'm suspecting the issue is embedding-related: the full title scores lower than just \"CHLEBEK\" alone, either because the structural bonus isn't being applied correctly or the threshold calculation is excluding the full title from the scoring baseline. But wait—there's also that 25-candidate cap that sorts and prioritizes candidates...\n\nSorting candidates by priority... the sorting logic prioritizes all-caps entries first, then short ones, so \"CHLEBEK\" ranks higher than longer all-caps phrases. With 36 input lines generating around 57 candidates through single and multi-line combinations, the hard filters would likely reduce that to 30-40 survivors before the top 25 are selected. ingredient/body text lines would be filtered). So it's likely > 25 candidates!\n\nIn the pre-filter sort: all-caps items first (including \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" and \"CHLEBEK\"), then short (≤5 words) first within each group. \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" has 6 words > 5, so it's \"long\". \"CHLEBEK\" has 1 word ≤ 5, so it's \"short\". The sort puts short all-caps BEFORE long all-caps. So the top 25 would include \"CHLEBEK\" (short+allcaps) but possibly exclude \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (allcaps but long, 6 words).\n\nNow I'm realizing there are probably many short all-caps section headers scattered throughout—things like \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (3 words),