e. For the second failure with the stuffed peppers recipe, the bilingual detection should have caught it, but instead it's picking up \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" from line 6—an all-caps phrase that passes the hard filters but isn't recognized as metadata because the Polish \"NA X [ingredient]\" pattern isn't in the metadata patterns list.\n\nNow I need to work through the threshold calculation. If the bilingual detection suppresses the gyeran-jjim line, the threshold depends on comparing the raw scores of the title versus the all-caps line, accounting for the all-caps bonus. The title would need to score high enough to clear whatever threshold gets set by the second-highest candidate.\n\nThe real problem might be that \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" is embedding well because it resembles recipe page structure, making it score too high and set an unreasonably strict threshold that the actual title struggles to pass. guard: if only \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" passes threshold (and \"Faszerowana papryka\" fails), then the answer is \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\".\n\nAlternatively, if \"Faszerowana papryka\" also passes, there would be 1 all-caps in `allCapsSelected` → `selected = [highest scoring candidate]`. If \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" scores higher than \"Faszerowana papryka\" (due to allCapsBonus), it wins.\n\nThe core issue is:\n1. \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" is a Polish serving-size indicator that should be filtered by `looksLikeMetadata` but isn't (metadata patterns are English-only).\n2. The all-caps bonus gives \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" an advantage over the mixed-case correct title\n\nThe `isStructuralHeading` check wouldn't help either—\"NA\" only has 2 uppercase letters, falling short of the 4-letter threshold, so no structural bonus applies. Yet \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" still gains the 0.08 all-caps bonus while \"Faszerowana papryka\" gets none, which tips the scales when the multi-title guard collapses to the highest score. The real problem is that the metadata filter doesn't catch Polish serving-size patterns, allowing \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" to slip through and win on bonus points alone. only handles English patterns, so \"NA 3 PAPRYKI\" (a Polish serving size indicator) doesn't get flagged as metadata. The all-caps bonus then pushes it above \"Faszerowana papryka,\" and the multi-title guard picks the highest-scoring all-caps option. There's also a potential issue where if the bilingual embedding similarity falls below 0.4, the suppression fails and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" inflates the threshold, causing \"Faszerowana papryka\" to drop below it.\n\nFor \"CHLEBEK,\" the pre-filter's preference for short all-caps entries (≤5 words) might exclude the full title \"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\" (6 words) when there are many section headers competing. Even if the full title survives the pre-filter, the dedup rule favoring shorter matches could eliminate it in favor of the standalone \"CHLEBEK\" section heading unless the prefix filter intervenes.\n\nThe core issues are that metadata detection is English-only, the 25-candidate pre-filter's \"short wins\" sorting penalizes multi-word titles in text-heavy recipes, the all-caps bonus disproportionately favors short section headers, and the dedup \"shorter wins\" rule can conflict with the prefix filter. Now I'm going to write the feedback file, making sure to distinguish between what I can confirm and what I'm hypothesizing. I should also check if there's a logs directory with additional diagnostic information.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":502,"cache_read_input_tokens":31141,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":502},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bb9abb27-5877-4e65-9635-9fb1a076739a","uuid":"395edadf-b2f0-4744-9ca7-b2b05fc2b9b8"}
